Conveyor belts.

A conveyor belt is a stretch of floor that carries the player along while they stand on it. Step onto a belt and it slides you one tile at a time in the direction it runs, so you can be swept across a room, nudged toward a hazard, or routed around a course without taking a step yourself. The belt itself never moves — it's the surface that does the carrying. Its cousins in the construction set, the moving platform and the lift, also move the player but in a very different way; the three are compared below.

How a conveyor belt works.

A conveyor belt fills a rectangular area and lays down a floor tile across it, playing a continuous running-belt loop so the player can hear it. While the player stands anywhere inside the belt, it pushes them one tile in its set direction every time its speed interval elapses — so a smaller speed is a faster belt. The push is relentless and one-directional: to fight it, the player has to walk against the belt, and to escape it they have to step off the edge. The belt runs forever at the same speed and never reverses, so chaining several belts of different directions lets you steer the player around a path hands-free. On 3d maps the belt is volumetric, filling every height level between its minimum and maximum z.

The direction list adapts to the map mode. On 2d maps the options are left, right, down, and up, where down and up carry the player vertically. On topdown maps they are left, right, backward, and forward, carrying the player along the depth axis. On 3d maps all six are offered — left, right, backward, forward, down, and up — where backward and forward run along depth and down and up carry the player through height. A belt always runs along a single one of these axes.

How a conveyor belt differs from moving platforms and lifts.

Three construction entities move the player without the player walking, and the conveyor belt is the odd one out:

A moving platform is a traveling surface. The platform itself slides along a path through a bounding area, carrying whoever rides it from one place to another as a unit, and it can run in any direction — straight, diagonal, or, on 3d maps, up and down — reversing or snapping back at the ends. The rider goes wherever the platform goes.
A lift is the vertical special case of a traveling surface: a platform that oscillates straight up and down between a low and high point, carrying its rider through height.
A conveyor belt is a stationary surface. It never travels; instead it slides the player across its own fixed floor in one set direction and off the far edge. You aren't a passenger being taken somewhere — you're being conveyed across a stretch of ground you can walk against or step off of.

In short, a moving platform and a lift carry the player with the surface — you ride along and stay put on it — while a conveyor belt carries the player across the surface, pushing you along it. Reach for a moving platform or a lift when the floor should travel and take the player with it, and a conveyor belt when the floor should stay put and sweep the player across it.

Conveyor belt fields.

The conveyor belt form takes the following:

Coordinates. A minimum and maximum x and a minimum and maximum y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), marking the rectangular stretch of belt. A belt always spans a range, even on 2d maps.
Direction. Which way the belt carries the player. On 2d maps: left, right, down, or up, where down and up are vertical. On topdown maps: left, right, backward, or forward. On 3d maps: left, right, backward, forward, down, or up, where backward and forward run along depth and down and up carry the player through height.
Speed. Milliseconds between each one-tile push, so a smaller number is a faster belt.
Tile sound. The floor tile the belt surface is made of, which supplies its step, land, and fall sounds. Pick air for a belt with no surface sound.
Belt sound (a folder name from the belt sounds list, or none). The continuous running-belt loop played across the area. Pick none for a silent belt.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the tile list is focused in the form, press space to hear the tile's step clip, hold control and press L to hear its land clip, and hold control and press H to hear its fall clip. While the belt sound list is focused, press space to hear the running-belt loop.

Authoring conveyor belts by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a conveyor belt is written under the name belt: belt minx maxx miny maxy direction speed tile belttype. On 3d maps a minimum and maximum z follow the y pair: belt minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz direction speed tile belttype. Direction is a number — 1 for left, 2 for right, 3 for down (backward on topdown and 3d maps), and 4 for up (forward on topdown and 3d maps); on 3d maps 5 carries the player down through height and 6 up. The tile must match a platform tile folder name or the word air, and the belt sound must match a belt sounds folder name or the word none.
